`★ Insight ─────────────────────────────────────`
- **Lazy cancellation** is the key pattern: instead of O(n) filtering the queue array when chunks go out of range, just delete from the `pendingChunks` Set. The queue item is skipped in O(1) when dequeued — the Set acts as a live "still-wanted" registry.
- **`flushQueue()` as a test seam** follows the same philosophy as `resolveGLBPath` or `computeWalkBob` in this codebase — export a pure/synchronous escape hatch that tests can call without needing fake timer infrastructure. One consistent pattern beats multiple per-test workarounds.
`─────────────────────────────────────────────────`

**US-069 complete.** Summary:

- `ChunkManager.update()` now **queues** new chunks instead of loading synchronously
- Generation runs one chunk at a time via `requestIdleCallback` (browser) / `setTimeout(cb, 0)` (Node fallback) — yields control after each expensive chunk to prevent frame drops
- Unloading remains synchronous (chunks removed immediately when out of range)
- Out-of-range chunks are lazily cancelled from the pending set — no O(n) array filtering
- `flushQueue()` and `getPendingChunkCount()` exported for test control
- 4 new async behavior tests + all 34 existing tests updated with `flushQueue()` — **2081 tests, 0 failures**

